  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An international organization that sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee's recommendations for banking regulations\n\n5. The Egmont Group, which facilitates international cooperation between financial intelligence units\n\nMany countries have also implemented their own national anti-money laundering (AML) laws that align with these international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and the Proceeds of Crime Act in the United Kingdom.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
